         <abstract>
            <p>According to a famous theorem of Markoff, the indefinite quadratic forms with exceptionally large minima (greater than $\frac{1}{3}$ of the square root of the discriminant) are in 1:1 correspondence with the solutions of the Diophantine equation $p^2 + q^2 + r^2 = 3pqr$. By relating Markoff's algorithm for finding solutions of this equation to a problem of counting lattice points in triangles, it is shown that the number of solutions less than $x$ equals $C \log^2 3x + O(\log x \log \log^2 x)$ with an explicitly computable constant $C = 0.18071704711507$.\ldots Numerical data up to $10^{1300}$ is presented which suggests that the true error term is considerably smaller.</p>
          </abstract>
